We came from one goal down to earn a draw at Stamford Bridge and move five points clear at the top of the table.&nbsp;

After a full-blooded first-half, in which Chelsea’s Moises Caicedo was sent off for a lunging foul on Mikel Merino, the hosts took the lead from a corner just after the restart, through Trevoh Chalobah.

We started to push the ten men back after that, and drew level when Merino headed in from Bukayo Saka’s cross.

We couldn’t find the winner, though this result made it 17 games unbeaten in all competitions.

The atmosphere was typically crackling for another London derby, and the challenges were flying in too. Martin Zubimendi, Marc Cucurella and Cristhian Mosquera were all booked in the opening 12 minutes.&nbsp;

The first chance fell to us, when Eberechi Eze worked the ball to Bukayo Saka inside the area. He had time to steady himself but his low shot was saved by Robert Sanchez.

At the other end Declan Rice made a superb timely tackle on Pedro Neto as he pulled the trigger at close range.

Estevao then blasted over when well placed in the area.

Our defence started to come under pressure. It’s only the second time in the last 162 Premier League games that we lined up without either Gabriel or William Saliba in the side, after the Frenchman picked up a knock in training.

Mosquera partnered Piero Hincapie at the back, but it was Jurrien Timber who came across to make a superb challenge on Enzo Fernandez on 20 minutes when the Argentine was through on goal through the middle.&nbsp;

David Raya saved easily from a speculative Enzo shot and Joao Pedro overhit a pass inside the box on the half hour.&nbsp;

Then the big flash point of the half. Chelsea were reduced to 10 men when Caicedo caught Merino with a poor, studs up challenge. The referee was sent by the VAR to watch a replay of the foul, and upgraded his decision from yellow to red.&nbsp;

We now had the numerical advantage, and as the half ticked into injury-time we put together our best move of the opening 45 minutes.&nbsp;

Rice stormed forward on the left, and slipped the ball to Gabriel Martinelli, whose low drive was well stopped by Sanchez.

After a feisty first half which saw five yellow cards and one red dished out, the second period started in the worst possible way, when Chelsea went ahead.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;

Just two minutes after the restart Chalobah flicked on a corner at the near post, and it flew over everyone inside the far post.

We needed a response. On came Martin Odegaard and Noni Madueke, and on the hour mark we were level. Saka twisted past his man and lifted up a perfect cross for Merino to head home at close range.

There was no let up in the pace. Raya got down well to save from Liam Delap while Saka shot over on the angle at the other end.

Late on Merino forced another save from Sanchez, when he couldn’t get his shot from the edge of the area close enough to the corner.&nbsp;

We could have won it right at the end. Hincapie got to the byline and stood up a cross to the far post. Viktor Gyokeres - back after injury - was arriving but Timber also jumped for the ball, and his flick on took it just beyond the Swede.&nbsp;

And so both teams had to settle for a point from a blood and thunder derby.

After an intensive week, the big games keep coming. We are back at home on Wednesday to welcome Brentford to Emirates Stadium in the Premier League, and that’s followed next Saturday by a trip to Aston Villa.

